sex, England":"Pleshey, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hyde Hall, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pleshy, Essex, England":"Pleshy, Essex, England","Sudeley, Gloucestershire, England":"Sudeley, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1166–1242":"1166–1242","1162–1222":"1162–1222","1209–1228":"1209–1228","1134–1180":"1134–1180","1138–1166":"1138–1166","1228":"1228","1138":"1138","ca. 1209":"about 1209","1134":"1134","1222":"1222","1166":"1166","1242":"1242","14 January 1180":"14 January 1180","1162":"1162","1209":"1209","26 February 1222":"26 February 1222","1180":"1180","Pleshey, Essex, England":"Pleshey, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Hyde Hall, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Pleshy, Essex, England":"Pleshy, Essex, England","Sudeley, Gloucestershire, England":"Sudeley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stafford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name principally from Stafford (Staffordshire), but occasionally from other places with similar names, such as Stafford House in Ifield (Sussex), possibly East and West Stowford in East Down (Devon), and three minor places in Devon called Stafford, in Dolton, Broadhembury, and Colyton parishes. The places are all named with Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ as the final element, but have different initial elements. The Staffordshire placename has Old English <i>stæth</i> ‘river bank, shore’; Stafford in Colyton (Devon) has Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’; the Sussex placename has Old English <i>stēor</i> ‘steer, bullock’; East and West Stowford (Devon) have Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’; Stafford in Dolton and Stafford in Broadhembury (Devon) may have Old English <i>stæth</i>, <i>stān</i>, or <i>stæf</i>.","Irish (Wexford): variant of   Stocker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stocker","meanings":["German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>): topographic name for someone living by a tree stump (see   Stock   3) or an occupational name for a tree cutter, from Middle High German <i>stocken</i> ‘to clear land’.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>); Dutch: occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stocker</i> ‘jailer’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>stokker</i> ‘one who sells stockfish’ (fish dried in the air without salt). This was the usual source of the name in medieval London, where a bylaw of 1419 stated that no <i>stokker</i> should board a ship to buy fish (presumably in order to forestall the market)."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Stafford was born in 1166, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Piers de Lutegareshale, was 32 and her mother, Maud Stafford, was 28. She had at least 1 daughter with John Sudeley. She died in 1242, in Sudeley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1166–1242":"1166–1242","1162–1222":"1162–1222","1209–1228":"1209–1228","1134–1180":"1134–1180","1138–1166":"1138–1166","1228":"1228","1138":"1138","ca. 1209":"umbes 1209","1134":"1134","1222":"1222","1166":"1166","1242":"1242","14 January 1180":"14. jaanuar 1180","1162":"1162","1209":"1209","26 February 1222":"26. veebruar 1222","1180":"1180","Pleshey, Essex, England":"Pleshey, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hyde Hall, Herefor